Introduction

The coronavirus disease has greatly impacted the lifestyle of human beings all over the globe in 2020. The outbreak started in Wuhan, China in December of 2019, and the virus is known as COVID-19. In March 2020, COVID-19 was declared as a pandemic by the World Health Organization (WHO). As researchers all around the world are racing to develop a vaccine for COVID-19, there are some studies that intrigued us. Researchers of Hydroxychloroquine, which is a drug used to treat malaria, have expressed previous parasitic viral infections (mainly malaria) can reduce the symptoms of COVID-19. A similar research also shows a correlation between Chloroquine, which is a stronger drug used to treat parasitic viruses and other auto-immune diseases, and the SARS virus, which also belongs to the coronavirus family. Those previous studies have motivated us to explore several findings in the datasets of COVID-19 and malaria cases.

This study is divided into two parts. For the first part, we will break down the statistics of COVID-19 to evaluate how the factors contribute to the COVID-19 result of each country. The factors include government stringency, population, age, gdp, health conditions, health care facilities, citizen’s life expectancy, and human development index (hdi). The second part is to study whether the prevalence of malaria impacts COVID-19 results. These findings may be useful in terms of slowing the spread of COVID-19, and strategically prioritizing the distributions of COVID-19 vaccine.

Raw Data

The main dataset we are using for this study contains the statistics of COVID-19 of all countries. The dataset can be found at https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus-source-data, and we name it covid. Another dataset we use for the second part of this study contains the statistics of malaria in 2017, which can be found at https://www.kaggle.com/imdevskp/malaria-dataset?select=reported_numbers.csv. Here, we will only summarize the covid dataset.

Summary of Covid Dataset:

  • Format: CSV(available in multiple formats)
  • Link:https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus-source-data
  • Data access date:10th October 2020 (updates monthly)
  • Columns: 43(2 empty)
  • Rows:50000
  • Contains several null values, needs a lot of cleaning

After cleaning the data we focussed on major continents like Africa, Asia,Europe and North America. The data after cleaning for these continents are as follows:

  • Africa :9355 rows; 33 columns
  • Asia : 8005 rows; 33 columns
  • Europe : 13188 rows; 33 columns
  • NorthAmerica :7937 rows; 33 columns

We further selected only the important attributes which were needed for our analysis.

Data Cleaning

As this is a large dataset, we break them down into smaller datasets that only focus of one continent, which include Africa, Asia, Europe, and North America.

library(dplyr)
covid<- read.csv("owid-covid-data.csv")
covid_Africa<-covid %>% filter(continent=="Africa")
covid_Europe<-covid %>% filter(continent=="Europe")
covid_Asia<-covid %>% filter(continent=="Asia")
covid_North_America<-covid %>% filter(continent=="North America")

For efficient data cleaning, we developed the following function to repeatedly remove missing data.

delete.na <- function(DF, n=2) {
  DF[rowSums(is.na(DF)) <= n,]
}

The first step in data cleaning is to look for the numbers of missing value in each variables for all continents.

Data Analysis

There are two parts in this data analysis. The first part is to analyze the covid dataset, and explore any findings that may be useful in terms of stopping the spread of COVID-19. The questions we have for this dataset are as followed:

  1. Which country is worst affected?
  2. What is the impact of Government stringency on spread of COVID-19?
  3. Does population density have an impact on COVID-19?
  4. What is the impact of smoking on COVID-19?
  5. What is the impact of diabetes on COVID-19?
  6. Which state should first get the vaccine to minimize deaths?

For the second part, we will investigate the relationship between prevalence of malaria and COVID-19.

Part 1

Q1. Which countris worst affected?

First, let us look at the top countries that have the most cases in each continent.

covid_asia_filter <- covid_Asia %>% group_by(location) %>% summarise(count=sum(new_cases,na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
covid_asia_filter<- head(covid_asia_filter[order(-covid_asia_filter$count),],9)
ggplot(covid_asia_filter,aes(x=location,y=count,color=location,fill=location))+geom_col()+ scale_y_continuous(name='Count',labels= scales::comma)+theme_bw()+ggtitle("Asia Top 9")

covid_Africa_filter<-covid_Africa %>% group_by(location) %>% summarise(count=sum(new_cases,na.rm = TRUE))

covid_Africa_filter<- head(covid_Africa_filter[order(-covid_Africa_filter$count),],9)
ggplot(covid_Africa_filter,aes(x=location,y=count,color=location,fill=location))+geom_col()+scale_y_continuous(name='Count',labels= scales::comma)+theme_bw()+ggtitle("Africa Top 9")

covid_Europe_filter<-covid_Europe %>% group_by(location) %>% summarise(count=sum(new_cases,na.rm = TRUE))

ggplot(covid_Europe_filter,aes(x=location,y=count,color=location,fill=location))+geom_col()+scale_y_continuous(name='Count',labels= scales::comma)+theme_bw()+ggtitle("Europe Top 9")

ggplot(covid_North_America_filter,aes(x=location,y=count,color=location,fill=location))+geom_col()+scale_y_continuous(name='Count',labels= scales::comma)+theme_bw()+ggtitle("North America Top 9")

As we can see from the graphs above, the country with most cases in each continent is India for Asia, Russia for Europe, South Africa for Africa, and United States for North America. Among all the top countries in all continents, Russia has the most cases, which is more than one million total cases. However, total case of a country does not indicate how well the country handle the pandemic, and how bad the country is affected. When we take the population of a country into account, the top 6 countries that have highest total cases per 10k population are Bahrain, Qatar, Andora, Aruba, Israel, and Vatican. The graph is shown below:

covid$date<-mdy(covid$date)
data4<-covid %>% filter(date=='2020-10-16') %>% summarise(location,total_cases,population) 
data4$total_casesper10k <- (data4$total_cases/data4$population)*100 

data4<-data4[order(-data4$total_casesper10k),]

data5<-head(data4)

ggplot(data5,aes(location,total_casesper10k,color=location,size=population))+geom_point()+theme_bw()

However, the graph above again does not indicate how bad a country is affected. That is because many countries, especially developing countries do not test people as much as developed countries do. This leads to bias because there would be cases that are not reported. Hence, we include the number of total test into our analysis by developing this equation: Comparable=total_cases/(population*total_tests). We use this variable to plot the following graph, and we can conclude that the worst affected country is Costa Rica.

compare2<-covid%>%filter(date=='2020-10-13')
compare2$comparable <- (compare2$total_cases/(compare2$population*compare2$total_tests)) 
compare2<-compare2[order(-compare2$comparable),]
compare3<-head(compare2,10)
ggplot(compare3,aes(x=location,y=comparable,color=location,size=population))+geom_point()

Q2. What is the impact of Government stringency on spread of COVID-19?

The correlation between government stringency and death rate is shown in the graph below:

strigency<-covid %>% filter(location=='India'|location=='United States'|location=='Russia'|location=='Italy')   
strigency %>% ggplot(aes(x=date,y=new_deaths_per_million,shape=location,color=stringency_index))+
  geom_point()+theme_bw()
## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

The higher the stringency index, the stricter the policies a country have on COVID-19. In other words, the country with 100 stringency index is the strictest. Looking at the graph above, countries with higher death rate have higher stringency index to control the spread of the virus.

Q3. Does population density have an impact on COVID-19?

The graph below shows the correlation between population density and new cases:

dens<-covid[order(-covid$population_density),]
dens<-covid[order(covid$population_density),]

dens %>% filter(location == "Monaco"|location=="Singapore"|location=="Hong Kong"|location=="Gibraltar"|location=="Bahrain"|location == "Greenland"|location=="Mongolia"|location=="Namibia"|location=="Australia"|location=="Iceland") %>%  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = new_cases,color=location)) + geom_line()+theme_bw()
## Warning: Removed 44 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

As we can see that, the higher the population density of a country, the higher the amount of new cases. However, some countries manage to control the spread, so even though they have peaks at the beginning of the outbreak, the numbers of new cases decrease rapidly.

Q4. What is the impact of smoking on COVID-19?

The graph below shows a direct correlation between the number of smokers to the number of new deaths that is caused by COVID-19:

smoking<-covid[order(covid$male_smokers,covid$female_smokers),]

smoking<-covid[order(-covid$male_smokers,-covid$female_smokers),]

Q6. Which state should first get the vaccine to minimize deaths?

To determine which states in the United States that should be prioritized the distribution of COVID-19 vaccine, we need to look at two variables, which are age and number of total case. The graph below shows the impact of age on the mean total cases of all countries. There is no strong correlation between the ratio of elders and mean total cases, but it is generally believed that older people are more susceptible to COVID-19. Here is the graph:

library(tidyr)
age <- covid %>%  group_by(location) %>%
  summarise(mean_cases=mean(total_cases_per_million, na.rm = TRUE),
            aged_65=mean(aged_65_older),
            aged_70=mean(aged_70_older))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
age <- age %>% gather("aged_65":"aged_70", key = "old_age", value = "elders.per.million")

age %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = elders.per.million, y = mean_cases, colour = old_age)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")+theme_bw()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 56 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 56 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Part 2

Key Question: Does malaria prevalence decrease COVID-19 deaths?

Now we will analyse the covid cases in countries that are heavily impacted by malaria to those where the prevalance is non-existent. We chose western countries like US,Canada and Italy for the analysis.

malaria<-covid %>% filter( location=='Uganda'| location=='Mozambique' ) %>% group_by(location)%>%summarise(date,total_deaths,population,location) 
malaria<-delete.na(malaria,0)

vis_miss(malaria)

non_malaria <-covid %>% filter(location=='United States' |location=='Italy'| location=='Canada') %>% group_by(location) %>% summarise(location,date,total_deaths,population)
ggplot(malaria,aes(x=date,y=total_deaths,color=location))+
  geom_line()+geom_line(non_malaria,mapping=(aes(x=date,y=total_deaths,color=location)))+theme_bw()
## Warning: Removed 185 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

But as we observe the data for the African countries is missing a lot of values and cannot be used to obeserve a pattern. In order to solve this problem we used data from India to draw conclusion. India has the 7th largest malaria infestation in the world and there are areas where the infestation is maximum. Some states do not have many cases of malaria and hence we used this to get a better understanding. We choose 4 states: 1. Tamil Nadu 2. Andhra Pradesh 3. Odisha 4. Jharkhand

The first 2 states do not have very minimal presence of malaria and the last 2 have a high prevalence of malaria. The following graph shows the statistics: https://i0.wp.com/localhost/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/india-api.gif

Since these states have very similar population,GDP and other factors a comparison will be very useful to solve our case. The following graph shows the comparison

india<-read.csv('covid-india.csv')
india<-delete.na(india,0)
india$Date<-dmy(india$Date)

india_compare<-india %>% filter(Region=='Andhra Pradesh'|Region=='Jharkhand'|Region=='Tamil Nadu'|Region=='Odisha')
india_compare %>% ggplot(aes(x=Date,y=Confirmed.Cases,color=Region))+geom_line()+theme_bw()

india_compare %>% ggplot(aes(x=Date,y=Death,color=Region))+geom_line()

Conclusion: From the comparative study we understand that the number of covid cases and the increase in covid cases in malaria impacted areas is very low as compared to areas where there is low prevalence. This low spread can be due to the higher usage of the drug Hydroxycholoroquine (HCQ) which is used to treat malaria and some auto immune diseases (There is a correlation and causation may or may not be true). A similar pattern was observed between Choloroquine(A stronger but similar drug as HCQ) and SARS(a virus of COVID family).
